every time we take a step forward it feels like we take leaps backward. the amount of anti-queer legislation i’ve seen in the media lately is frightening; to say the least. even though my rights are protected where I live, currently around the US we are losing equality for trans health care, bathroom rights, and the privacy of trans identities in school (the only place many trans individuals can feel safe). attacks on the trans and queer community are only continuing to amplify so I encourage you to stay up-to-date, alert, and ready to show up. help the uneducated understand that we are just trying to exist. these attacks will soon enough negatively impact not only the trans and queer community but all minorities. a main concern is the safety of children yet we aren’t the ones sexualizing children, we are being sexualized based on stereotypes, stigmas and what’s in our pants. the public lack of education of trans people continues to tarnish our reputation as a community. my genitals do NOT equal my gender identity nor will it ever be a concern for the safety of children. we are just trying to live as our most authentic selves. let us keep our medical care, use the restroom in peace and exist. we have bigger issues to worry about for crying out loud.

Happy Trans Day of Visibility! From being in GLAAD’s 20 under 20 to presenting at the 34th annual GLAAD AWARDS, I couldn’t feel more seen right now. Being able to be on stage heals the inner child that was once a young trans kid searching for other youth like myself. Last night I was asked how I feel about the anti-queer legislation going on right now A LOT. As someone who has experienced lawmakers threatening my rights with (for example) bills that pertain to simply using the restroom, I can’t believe it’s happening again but in even more life-threatening ways. History is repeating itself. This isn’t my first rodeo which is sad to say because I’m only 18 years old. It feels like I can’t thrive at times like this, but the gag is I am! What got me through hard times like this was the supportive community and allies I had. It becomes tiresome speaking up for yourself every day, but when you have people who understand your struggle and are willing to speak up, we make change. That being said, trans identities are threatened because we embody pure certainty in ourselves, but that makes us GORGEOUS. Thank you GLAAD for giving me my flowers last night, it was a breath of fresh air and truly unforgettable.
